President Muhammadu Buhari has reassured Nigerians that the withdrawal of the military from areas where peace had been restored would not be done in a manner that would expose the communities to more risks of attacks. The president, in a statement issued in Abuja, yesterday, by his media aide, Garba Shehu, said that the withdrawal of the troops would be gradual and carefully planned so as not to jeopardise the success recorded by the military. Commenting on the concerns and appeals from governors and community leaders over the proposed action, President Buhari said that the “administration will not abandon citizens in need of protection.” He, therefore, urged Nigerians, especially public affairs analysts, to study the statement after the security council meeting with service chiefs that the withdrawal of troops will be done after an “assessment” to determine the areas where peace had returned to enable civil authorities assume full control. Buhari said that where it is determined that the withdrawal will not in any way jeopardise the peace already achieved, the military pullout will be in a careful and gradual way. He said: “You don’t need to worry. We will not expose our people and their communities to harm or danger. “The withdrawal is to allow the military focus on its primary duty of defending the nation against external aggression. It is the duty of the police to handle internal security since Nigeria is not at war. “The Nigeria Security and Civil Defence Corps will support the police to provide internal security. When it is time to withdraw, nothing will be rushed,’’ he added.  